  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: This edited volume brings together essays by Dussel and his interlocutors (including Karl-Otto Apel), assessing Dussel's critiques of discourse ethics, evaluations of Marx, Levinas, Habermas, and development of a philosophy from the underside of Eurocentric modernity. Contributors examine Dussel's concept of an ethics of the impoverished and his articulation of a Latin American theoretical perspective. The volume includes Dussel's own responses to critics.

  RELEVANCE: Essential collection documenting the Dussel-Apel debate and providing multiple perspectives on Dussel's ethics. Includes Apel's defense of discourse ethics and Dussel's response. Michael Barber's chapter examines Dussel's appropriation of Levinas. The volume as a whole demonstrates the international philosophical reception of Dussel's liberation philosophy and the key debates it has provoked.

